	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />English grammar is actually quite simple when compared to most languages... What makes english hard for me is pronunciation. There are basicaly no rules for pronunciation in english, if you consider that "laughter" is pronounced so differently from "slaughter" and the only difference in spelling is the "s". 
<br />
<br />When I see a new word in english I won't dare saying it until I hear someone else (on TV or whatever) saying it, 'cause only them I'll know the actual pronunciation. Sometimes I can't even connect a written word to a word I've heard many times on TV. Of course the internet made it all easier, with phonetic guides and audio clips, which I can seek in case of doubt.
<br />
<br />Also, the vowels sound very differently from most other languages (they seem swapped somehow - but just in some cases, because even in english their sounds vary so much), and consonants require too much tongue rolling. For example, "r" in english sounds much more like "rw", which requires much more tongue and lip movement than the clean "r" from, say, japanese.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


