<br /> My youngest son is 6 and halfway through 1st grade. Learning how to read and *pronounce* words he's never seen before is just crazy, and it seems like I'm always telling him, "Ok, this one is an exception. It sounds like this...".  Why "s<span style="text-decoration: underline">o</span>n" sounds like "s<span style="text-decoration: underline">u</span>n" and 's<span style="text-decoration: underline">oo</span>n'  like 'y<span style="text-decoration: underline">ou</span>' and not 'look' or 'took' but definitely 'g<span style="text-decoration: underline">oo</span>n'. And to look for early queues or hints in the sentence about when to pronounce 'read' as 'reed' or 'red'. Etc.

		

